label chapter8:

    # [Scene: New Embankment | Morning after ribbon-cutting]

    scene bg ch8_6b08b4_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle, rising strings — cautious optimism]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low surf, the distant chatter of the harbor, the clank of a handcart; gulls calling like punctuation]
    # [Smell: Tar and wet concrete undercut by briny air and the faint sweetness of disturbed peat]
    "You walk the length of the embankment with your notebook closed against your chest, but your fingers know its weight anyway. The ribbon is a memory along the edge of your mind — claps, flashbulbs, Celine's"
    "practiced smile — and the physical thing now is taller, rawer, and more immediate: sand pulled and compacted, concrete poured into molds, the skeleton of drainage channels sketched and then filled."
    "At first the surface reads as a victory. Kids push at the new railing and laugh; Oba stands a little apart, hat in hand, eyes on the sea; Maya hands you a thermos — one of"
    "her small acts of care. You let the warmth of those simple things settle into you. This is work that will matter. This is what you came back for."
    "Then Leyna calls your name and the way she says it pulls your shoulders straight. She stands by a cluster of contractors, tablet in hand, brows furrowed. The tablet screen reflects in the slanting light like a small, furious tide."
    show dr_leyna_ortiz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_leyna_ortiz "Alys—' (she hesitates, then softer) 'You need to see this."
    "You fall into the rhythm of inspection: eyes to meter, fingers to seam, questioning the curve of a slope the way you used to count tidal lines. The data Leyna shows is a cross-section of what"
    "was supposed to be below that smooth face: layered geotextile, a specific salt-tolerant fill, engineered pools for run-off, an ecological filter zone by the toe. What you see on-site — the soil texture pressed under boots,"
    "the smell of a different binder where the soil meets concrete — does not match the cross-section."
    "You feel the hollow open in your stomach that used to come before storms; familiarity sharpens, then steadies. There are deviations. They are not catastrophic in the way a levee collapse is catastrophic — they are"
    "incremental, a pattern of compromises: one omitted layer here, a substitute aggregate there, a drainage pipe with a different gauge. Individually, each tweak reads like a technician's decision. Together, they sketch a small erosion of the"
    "safeguards you and Leyna fought for."
    show alys_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    alys_maren "How far off are we?"
    "Dr. Leyna Ortiz leans close to the screen, fingers scrolling. Her breath smells like the thermos Maya gave you — coffee and salt."
    show dr_leyna_ortiz at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_leyna_ortiz "Not all of it is documented. Some materials were logged with generic codes. The compaction tests are—' (she swallows) '—they passed, but the sampling points are fewer than the plan called for. And look at this: these drainage trenches were rerouted."
    "You hold the tablet and feel the coolness of it against your palm as if it could conduct certainty into you. The crowd on the embankment functions around your small orbit: Ronan laughing with a volunteer,"
    "Ivo tightening a bolt in a corner where permissions are still wet, contractors wiping sweat with the backs of their hands."
    "Ivo Calder approaches, gait efficient and grounded; there is dust on his sleeves and a camera slung at his hip. Up close, his expression is the one you have seen a thousand times — the light of someone used to solving problems with hands and tomorrow's coffee."
    hide dr_leyna_ortiz
    show ivo_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ivo_calder "You look like you swallowed a storm, Alys.' (he grins but the line at the corner of his mouth says he's bracing) 'What did Leyna find?"
    "You hand him the tablet. He scrolls, squints, then bites the inside of his cheek."

    ivo_calder "These are not the specs we agreed on.' (he looks up, searching your face) 'If they cut corners, we fix them. We shore them up. We show people protection now, not delay them for paperwork."
    "There's a hard, urgent logic in his words — immediate protection is visible, measurable in the sleep that returns to kitchens and nets left to dry. You feel the pull of that sleep in the faces"
    "around you. You can already hear Celine's future ribbon-cutting speech in the back of your mind, the cameras that will file this work into tomorrow's headlines."
    "Celine Harrow arrives, immaculate despite the grit, her coat folded just so. Her arrival reframes the scene: the air tightens, public and private under one roofless sky."
    hide alys_maren
    show celine_harrow at right:
        zoom 0.7

    celine_harrow "Alys. Leyna. I wanted to thank you both again — this is a proud day for Saltwick.' (she extends a hand that smells faintly of perfume and municipal polish) 'Everything looks splendid."
    "Her smile does not diffuse the questions; it amplifies the stakes. Her priorities have always been to move large things; the embankment is her signature. You can see the cameras' memory already filing her name beside the wall."
    hide dr_leyna_ortiz
    show alys_maren at center:
        zoom 0.7

    alys_maren "Celine—' (you keep your tone even) 'There are discrepancies. Some of the materials and routing don't match the environmental safeguards in our contract."
    "Celine's eyes sharpen in a way that is not entirely unreadable. She inclines her head, calculating."

    celine_harrow "Contracts are documents; construction is reality. Where there are necessary, pragmatic adjustments, we document and proceed. The town needs safety now, Alys. We cannot be paralysed by perfect plans."
    "Your chest tightens. Pragmatic adjustments are often where long-term intent dissipates into expediency. But the sound of a child laughing on the walkway, the way Oba's shoulders relax just a fraction when he leans on the"
    "rail — those immediate solace points are real, too. The trajectory of your work has always been to hold both: the care for people now and the work that ensures the people will be there in"
    "fifty years."
    "You feel the choice pressing its outline against everything: ethics versus optics, science versus solace. And because this is Saltwick, because everyone you love sleeps to the rhythm of tides not ledgers, you understand that any decision you make will ripple."
    "Oba Kofi, who has been quiet until now, walks up with the steady, careful step of someone used to reading tides and time. The scent of old rope clings to him. He places his hand lightly on the new railing, as if testing a pulse."
    hide ivo_calder
    show oba_kofi at left:
        zoom 0.7

    oba_kofi "We built things in my father's day that lasted because we remembered the shore. Not all shortcuts take away at once. Some take a little every year.' (he looks at you) 'But when the sea asks, you want the answer in good bones."
    "His voice is a kind of anchor. It reminds you that resilience is not only a present comfort — it's a pattern of future days."
    "Maya Maren gives you a small, fierce look. Her apron is streaked with paint; she leans in, a human firewall of familial care."
    hide celine_harrow
    show maya_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_maren "If you call for a halt, don't call it betrayal. Call it tending. People will understand tending."
    "You let her squeeze linger. The intimacy of family is permission and a tether. You are not making this decision alone; the town is right here, in how they stand and breathe and watch."

    menu:
        "Ask a contractor for the ship's manifest and the exact materials used":
            "You step forward, voice clear. A young foreman hands you a tablet, hands rough. He stammers through explanations, then grows defensive — then, when you show your steady gaze, practical. He opens a file. You feel the small relief of facts entering the room."
        "Pull Ivo aside and ask if he can patch deviations without public notice":
            "You lean toward Ivo. He studies the embankment like an engineer measuring a seam. He considers quick reinforcements — bolstering where needed. He says he can do it, quietly, but his jaw tightens at the privacy of it. You register the cost of quiet fixes."
        "Stay on the walkway and listen to the town; see what the people are saying first":
            "You step back to the railing and let the town speak. A volunteer jokes about the smooth finish. An elder worries aloud. Voices braid together into a pattern of hope and fear. You let that chorus weigh in before you speak."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose, briefly, in one of those small ways that does not resolve anything but orients you: you want the facts, you want to keep Ivo close, and you want the town to be heard. It"
    "is both messy and necessary — a set of small commitments consistent with what you have always tried to build."
    "You walk with Leyna to the maintenance trench. Her gloved hand hovers above the exposed layers; dust lifts like a memory. She taps a finger on a place where there should be woven fabric; there is only compacted fill."
    hide alys_maren
    show dr_leyna_ortiz at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_leyna_ortiz "If this were a test plot, I'd call it salvageable with rework. But under a public contract? We need transparency. Auditors need to confirm what was used and why."
    "You think of the municipal ledger you signed; you think of Celine's hand on the pen. You think of headlines that will headline success and quiet the questions. You think of Ronan — youthful, impatient — who will put his back into any wall you ask of him."
    hide oba_kofi
    show ivo_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ivo_calder "Delayed work risks losing trust and momentum,' he says again, gentler this time. 'We can present a remedial plan: shore up critical points now, schedule audits, make a public statement that we're committed to oversight. People see scaffolding and progress. They sleep sooner."
    "Celine folds her hands as if she were about to offer you a silk scarf. The scaffolding of her rhetoric is familiar and real: speed, funding, visible results. It works on many people. It worked on"
    "you for a moment when you signed the contract because you believed the funding would seed the restoration you care about."
    "You feel the tug between choices like a line across the sea: it hums, and in it there is possibility. The tone of the morning does not harden into scandal yet. There is air between accusation and action where repair — ethical and practical — can still happen."
    "Your internal monologue arranges the options like tools in your bag: you could demand audits and pause the work, a gamble on ethics and long-term trust; you could authorize completion and claim immediate safety, a trade"
    "that comforts now but might fray future foundations; or you could leak the discrepancies to force oversight, risking scandal but perhaps creating accountability that can't be negotiated away."
    "You picture the embankment in all its possible futures: robust and true; patched and secretly shaky; the spark of public outrage leading to stronger governance. The rising strings swell — not to doom, but to the shape of a choice that could carry Saltwick forward if handled with care."
    "Ivo Calder reaches for your hand, briefly — not a proposal, but an anchor. His palm is callused, familiar, and the touch is both a comfort and a reminder that the people you love want sleep tonight."

    ivo_calder "Whatever you choose, we'll stand with you. We always do.' (he adds, light but honest) 'But be ready for heat. People will ask why the work stopped, why we didn't let them see the wall finished."
    "Celine smiles in a way that could become a press photo; Leyna’s jaw is set; Oba watches the sea. Maya's grip on your sleeve is quiet but present. The town is a collection of breaths waiting on your exhale."

    menu:
        "Tell Leyna to call for an immediate audit while you prepare a public message":
            "You ask Leyna to make the call. She nods and her fingers fly across the tablet; the call is terse, professional, already moving toward process. You begin drafting the message in your head — firm, honest, rooted in care."
        "Tell Ivo to start reinforcing the most vulnerable sections today, quietly, while you dig deeper":
            "You whisper to Ivo. He nods once and walks off with a plan already forming. You feel the quiet momentum of action, but the hum of secrecy sits at the edges of it."

    # --- merge ---
    "You breathe in. The wind tastes like salt and possibility. You imagine the embankment aged by seasons: scarred, tended, or a publicity relic. In this liminal morning there is still room to choose how the story of this wall will be told."
    "You step back toward the cluster — for a moment a conductorless orchestra of purpose — and realize the decision must be made soon. Cameras hum in a nearby van; a reporter asks a quick question"
    "you half-answer with a nod. You are aware that delay itself will be read as a statement, that completion will be read as assurance, and that exposure will be read as both betrayal and salvation."
    "You sit on a low bale of compressed sand and close your eyes long enough to feel the sun on your lids. The compass at your wrist — your father's — clicks faintly as you move. It is an old thing that points you toward duty more than certainty."

    "You write, in your notebook — a single line, shaky then deliberate" "Hold to the shore, hold to one another."
    "The rising music resolves to a single bright chord. There is pressure, yes, and risk, but under it a pulse that says accountability can build trust if handled with care. This is not a descent into distrust; there is still a way forward that can knit safety and ethics together."
    "You stand, and the chapter of action presses against the page."

